WEBVTT

00:04.134 --> 00:04.352
.

00:04.395 --> 00:06.093
- In the criminal justice
system,

00:06.136 --> 00:07.485
sexually based offenses

00:07.529 --> 00:09.661
are considered
especially heinous.

00:09.705 --> 00:12.273
In New York City,
the dedicated detectives

00:12.316 --> 00:14.057
who investigate
these vicious felonies

00:14.101 --> 00:15.450
are members of an elite squad

00:15.493 --> 00:17.669
known as
the Special Victims Unit.

00:17.713 --> 00:20.281
These are their stories.

00:20.324 --> 00:21.934
[dramatic music]

00:21.978 --> 00:23.936
- You took my wife from me.

00:23.980 --> 00:25.634
- Elliot.

00:25.677 --> 00:28.419
- I wrote this.
Just read it.

00:28.463 --> 00:30.987
Your boss ordered a hit,
killing my wife.

00:31.031 --> 00:33.207
- I want to talk.
I need protection.

00:33.250 --> 00:34.338
- What is this?

00:34.382 --> 00:36.297
- It's just precautionary,
Izak.

00:39.126 --> 00:41.041
- Liv,
you mean the world to me.

00:41.084 --> 00:43.304
I am not gonna allow
these emotions

00:43.347 --> 00:45.262
to derail me from my mission.

00:45.306 --> 00:47.525
- Angela Wheatley is luck
to be alive.

00:47.569 --> 00:50.311
Does your doctor think you'll
be well enough to testify?

00:50.354 --> 00:52.878
- Ah!
- Look what I found.

00:52.922 --> 00:55.098
- Olivia Benson.

00:55.142 --> 00:57.796
Elliot, now I understand.
She's a knockout.

00:57.840 --> 00:59.320
- Get him out of here.

01:09.156 --> 01:11.114
Hey.

01:11.158 --> 01:12.420
- Thanks for coming, Olivia.

01:12.463 --> 01:15.553
- How you all doing?
- We're okay.

01:15.597 --> 01:17.338
- And--and I'm really
getting through things.

01:17.381 --> 01:20.210
- Good. Ah, you shaved.

01:20.254 --> 01:23.257
It's nice to see your face.
- It was time.

01:26.434 --> 01:28.088
- Happy belated birthday, Mom.

01:28.131 --> 01:31.656
We love you. We miss you.

01:31.700 --> 01:34.790
Every single day.

01:34.833 --> 01:37.749
[sentimental music]

01:37.793 --> 01:44.713
♪

01:48.108 --> 01:49.152
- Italian for lunch?

01:49.196 --> 01:51.459
Kathy's favorite.
- Sounds perfect.

01:51.502 --> 01:53.330
- Actually, Dad,
I was gonna go meet Sara.

01:53.374 --> 01:54.984
Is that okay?

01:55.027 --> 01:56.246
- You got a date now?

01:56.290 --> 01:58.422
- She's not a date.
She's my study partner.

01:58.466 --> 01:59.902
- All right, well, check in,
text.

01:59.945 --> 02:01.164
- Okay.

02:01.208 --> 02:03.166
- Good.
Show him you trust him.

02:03.210 --> 02:04.689
- Trust, but verify.

02:04.733 --> 02:06.430
I got a tracking app
on his cell.

02:06.474 --> 02:08.432
- I can't hear this.
- And security cameras at home.

02:08.476 --> 02:11.261
- We'll meet you guys.

02:11.305 --> 02:14.221
- God, Eli's growing up fast.

02:16.397 --> 02:18.399
- Last nine months
have been a blur.

02:18.442 --> 02:20.575
Until Wheatley goes to trial,
there's no closure.

02:20.618 --> 02:24.056
- Carisi said that Wheatley's
out of postponements.

02:24.100 --> 02:25.449
The clock is ticking.

02:25.493 --> 02:27.234
- Make it tick faster.

02:27.277 --> 02:31.194
[suspenseful music]

02:31.238 --> 02:34.632
- Mr. Baptiste, Mr. Carisi,
I'm denying People's motion

02:34.676 --> 02:36.721
for this evidence
to be admitted at trial.

02:36.765 --> 02:39.159
- Your Honor, Izak Bekher
was Richard Wheatley's

02:39.202 --> 02:42.466
right-hand man, his bodyguard,
his head of security,

02:42.510 --> 02:45.817
the architect of the bomb
that killed Kathy Stabler.

02:45.861 --> 02:48.342
His taped confession is crucial
to the state's case.

02:48.385 --> 02:50.126
- And inadmissible as hearsay,

02:50.170 --> 02:53.347
as my predecessor admonished
you three months ago,

02:53.390 --> 02:55.175
since Mr. Bekher
isn't available

02:55.218 --> 02:56.741
for cross-examination.

02:56.785 --> 02:58.221
- Mr. Bekher can't
make himself available

02:58.265 --> 02:59.483
because he's presumed dead,

02:59.527 --> 03:01.703
most likely at the hand
of Richard Wheatley.

03:01.746 --> 03:03.705
- The larger point remains,
the state has not proved

03:03.748 --> 03:07.317
that my client, by "violence,
threats, or chicanery,"

03:07.361 --> 03:09.493
caused Bekher
to be unavailable.

03:09.537 --> 03:11.321
- I'm agreeing with you,
Counselor.

03:11.365 --> 03:13.323
Take yes for an answer.

03:13.367 --> 03:14.846
Motion denied.
- In that case,

03:14.890 --> 03:16.761
we move to set
an immediate trial date.

03:16.805 --> 03:18.502
- Actually,
that won't be possible.

03:18.546 --> 03:19.982
- Excuse me?
- I need time

03:20.025 --> 03:21.331
to find new representation.

03:21.375 --> 03:22.898
I'm firing my lawyer.
- What?

03:22.941 --> 03:24.508
- Sorry, Lisa,
you're fine for motions,

03:24.552 --> 03:26.031
but you're not cut out
for trial.

03:26.075 --> 03:29.426
My right as a defendant,
if I understand that correctly?

03:29.470 --> 03:31.950
- Yes, that of course,
is your right, Mr. Wheatley.

03:31.994 --> 03:33.952
You have one week.

03:33.996 --> 03:37.434
♪

03:37.478 --> 03:40.002
- The long-anticipated trial
of Richard Wheatley

03:40.045 --> 03:41.960
has been delayed once again.

03:42.004 --> 03:44.963
Wheatley has changed lawyers
for the fourth time

03:45.007 --> 03:47.227
since he's been accused
of the contract killing

03:47.270 --> 03:48.315
of Kathy Stabler--

03:48.358 --> 03:49.751
- How'd that go?
- Not good.

03:49.794 --> 03:51.753
- Change of lawyers.
We should've seen that coming.

03:51.796 --> 03:53.407
- And somehow they
get Judge Ellery?

03:53.450 --> 03:55.365
With what we had on that guy,
how is he still on the bench?

03:55.409 --> 03:57.715
- You have to ask?
- Paranoia won't help us.

03:57.759 --> 03:59.587
- Angela Wheatley,
Wheatley's ex-wife,

03:59.630 --> 04:01.415
is expected to take the stand,

04:01.458 --> 04:03.547
after turning state's evidence
and implicating--

04:03.591 --> 04:05.549
- We'll need your help
prepping witnesses.

04:05.593 --> 04:07.334
- Wheatley's not
going down easy.

04:07.377 --> 04:09.510
- This guy doesn't want
to spend one more minute

04:09.553 --> 04:12.034
of his life in jail.

04:12.077 --> 04:14.515
- I hope to work with you,
Mr. Wheatley.

04:14.558 --> 04:16.865
- We'll be in touch.
- All right.

04:20.172 --> 04:22.479
- Nice ass for Yale Law,
but no.

04:22.523 --> 04:25.830
- Just one more, Mr. Wheatley.

04:25.874 --> 04:28.050
- Send him in.

04:28.093 --> 04:32.184
Born in South Bronx,
full scholarship to Harvard.

04:32.228 --> 04:35.449
Impressive.
- And yet I'm here.

04:35.492 --> 04:37.668
- I've done well
by hiring self-made men.

04:37.712 --> 04:39.496
They know how to hustle,
and they work twice as hard.

04:39.540 --> 04:41.324
The only thing that gets
in their way,

04:41.368 --> 04:44.109
they always have a chip.

04:44.153 --> 04:46.329
What's yours?

04:46.373 --> 04:48.331
- I don't suffer fools,

04:48.375 --> 04:50.725
especially as clients.

04:50.768 --> 04:53.031
Why don't you tell me
your side?

04:53.075 --> 04:56.557
♪

04:57.906 --> 05:00.865
[dramatic music]

05:00.909 --> 05:07.829
♪

05:44.692 --> 05:46.476
- Angela, let me help you.
- No.

05:46.520 --> 05:48.609
I need to do this myself.

05:48.652 --> 05:51.612
- Miss Wheatley,
nice to see you again.

05:51.655 --> 05:55.267
- I'm sorry. Uh, we've met?

05:55.311 --> 05:56.747
- ADA Carisi.

05:56.791 --> 05:58.880
I'm prosecuting
your ex-husband.

05:58.923 --> 06:02.449
- Yes. Of course.

06:02.492 --> 06:04.842
[sighs]
You wanted to prep?

06:04.886 --> 06:07.845
- Yeah.

06:07.889 --> 06:09.891
- I don't need
protective custody.

06:09.934 --> 06:12.023
Nobody knows
I'm gonna testify.

06:12.067 --> 06:15.026
- We're gonna have to inform
the defense before trial.

06:15.070 --> 06:17.638
- Right, you're gonna have
to tell my dad.

06:17.681 --> 06:20.380
- Well, if that's a problem,
you need to say something now.

06:20.423 --> 06:22.425
- After what he did
to my grandfather,

06:22.469 --> 06:24.035
my mother,

06:24.079 --> 06:26.037
he's dead to me.

06:26.081 --> 06:27.517
[tense music]

06:27.561 --> 06:29.127
- You've accepted my offer?

06:29.171 --> 06:31.608
- Whoever said crime doesn't
pay wasn't a lawyer.

06:31.652 --> 06:33.567
- So you see that I'm innocent?

06:33.610 --> 06:36.221
I'm being framed
for a crime I didn't commit.

06:36.265 --> 06:37.745
- I see that there's
ample opportunity

06:37.788 --> 06:39.747
for reasonable doubt,
but we got a lot of work to do.

06:42.619 --> 06:43.881
- What do you want to know?

06:43.925 --> 06:48.233
- Anything you told Izak,
Angela, or Richie.

06:48.277 --> 06:49.844
Anything they told you.

06:54.588 --> 06:56.720
- Rafael Barba.
You know him, right?

06:56.764 --> 06:58.809
- I do.
- He's representing Wheatley.

06:58.853 --> 07:00.332
He good?

07:00.376 --> 07:02.509
- Very.
- Hey, Liv.

07:02.552 --> 07:04.032
Barba's here, you want me
to tell him to wait?

07:04.075 --> 07:06.295
- No. Counselor.

07:07.557 --> 07:10.299
- Rafael Barba.
- Elliot Stabler.

07:10.342 --> 07:12.954
- Oh, I'm sorry for your loss.
- Are you?

07:15.652 --> 07:18.002
Then why are you defending
the man who killed my wife?

07:20.962 --> 07:22.790
Liv, I'll see you later.

07:22.833 --> 07:29.753
♪

07:32.147 --> 07:34.671
- Why are you doing this?
- Because it's wrong.

07:34.715 --> 07:36.456
If the DA's office can
bring a case like this

07:36.499 --> 07:38.327
against someone
as wealthy as Wheatley,

07:38.370 --> 07:39.502
then that gives them license

07:39.546 --> 07:41.156
to railroad any defendant
at any time.

07:41.199 --> 07:44.028
- Richard Wheatley is guilty.
- Then let the state prove it.

07:44.072 --> 07:45.595
That's how this works.
Think about it.

07:45.639 --> 07:47.249
30 RICO charges
that they let slide.

07:47.292 --> 07:48.946
30, but they cherry-picked
this one?

07:48.990 --> 07:51.993
Why?
Because one PP pressured them?

07:52.036 --> 07:53.995
- I get that that's how you're
justifying this to yourself,

07:54.038 --> 07:58.434
but I am asking you
not to take this case.

07:58.478 --> 08:00.131
- Be careful what you wish for.

08:00.175 --> 08:02.612
I step aside,
whatever shark Wheatley hires

08:02.656 --> 08:05.310
will put not just the NYPD
and Stabler on trial,

08:05.354 --> 08:07.922
but you--you!

08:07.965 --> 08:10.141
Not just your partnership
with Stabler,

08:10.185 --> 08:11.578
but your relationship.

08:11.621 --> 08:13.014
He should never
have been allowed

08:13.057 --> 08:15.538
anywhere near
this investigation, Liv.

08:15.582 --> 08:17.801
They'll eviscerate you
on the stand.

08:17.845 --> 08:20.108
Maybe end your career.
- So which is it?

08:20.151 --> 08:21.631
Are you protecting me?

08:21.675 --> 08:24.112
Or is this your
defense attorney outrage?

08:27.289 --> 08:30.031
Or is this about Stabler?
- I don't know Stabler.

08:34.688 --> 08:37.038
Maybe it's the first two
out of three.

08:41.956 --> 08:43.653
I know you're sure
that Wheatley is guilty.

08:43.697 --> 08:45.612
- I am.
- That does not give the NYPD

08:45.655 --> 08:47.831
the right to frame him.

08:49.485 --> 08:50.965
- Rafa.

08:51.008 --> 08:57.928
♪

09:05.980 --> 09:06.197
.

09:06.241 --> 09:09.374
- Day one of the long-awaited
trial of Richard Wheatley

09:09.418 --> 09:13.204
for the contract killing
of an NYPD detective's wife.

09:13.248 --> 09:16.294
- Wheatley had been looking at
RICO charges of racketeering,

09:16.338 --> 09:18.470
money laundering,
and drug trafficking.

09:18.514 --> 09:21.038
- But those charges
were dismissed as a result

09:21.082 --> 09:23.737
of his cooperation
with federal authorities.

09:23.780 --> 09:25.913
- Carisi, get any sleep?

09:25.956 --> 09:27.871
- Was up all night.
What about you guys?

09:27.915 --> 09:29.569
- Same.
- I slept like a baby.

09:29.612 --> 09:32.180
- Hey, Liv, heads up, Baptiste
is gonna take your direct.

09:32.223 --> 09:33.660
We'll both protect
on Barba's crossing.

09:33.703 --> 09:34.617
- I'm ready.
- All right.

09:34.661 --> 09:35.749
I'll see you inside.

09:37.751 --> 09:39.883
- Dominick, you look tired.

09:39.927 --> 09:41.711
- Not me.
I slept like a baby.

09:41.755 --> 09:44.845
- Good. You'll need it.

09:44.888 --> 09:47.804
[suspenseful music]

09:47.848 --> 09:52.548
♪

09:52.592 --> 09:55.203
- I arrived shortly
after the bomb went off.

09:55.246 --> 09:58.946
Um, Kathy Stabler
was badly injured

09:58.989 --> 10:01.078
and being loaded
into the ambulance.

10:01.122 --> 10:03.428
- Captain Benson,
you're the head of SVU.

10:03.472 --> 10:06.257
Why were you called
to the scene of a car bomb?

10:06.301 --> 10:09.086
- Kathy was the wife
of my former partner,

10:09.130 --> 10:11.915
Detective Elliot Stabler,
so he requested me.

10:11.959 --> 10:13.656
- So you knew the victim?

10:13.700 --> 10:17.007
- I did, but I hadn't seen her
or Detective Stabler

10:17.051 --> 10:19.140
in over a decade.

10:19.183 --> 10:20.576
- What happened next, Captain?

10:20.620 --> 10:23.535
- Detective Stabler rode
with Kathy to the hospital.

10:23.579 --> 10:24.928
I met them there.

10:24.972 --> 10:26.451
- And as the jury has heard,

10:26.495 --> 10:30.151
she died from a ruptured spleen
a few days later.

10:30.194 --> 10:33.415
- A direct result of the
injuries that she sustained.

10:33.458 --> 10:34.721
- And SVU was part

10:34.764 --> 10:37.114
of the initial investigation--
why?

10:37.158 --> 10:39.943
- There was a lot
happening that night--

10:39.987 --> 10:42.642
protests in the neighborhood,

10:42.685 --> 10:45.993
two other police vehicles were
hit with Molotov cocktails.

10:46.036 --> 10:49.474
It was a
all-hands-on-deck situation.

10:49.518 --> 10:53.522
- Was this car bombing
in any way related

10:53.565 --> 10:54.915
to those other incidents?

10:54.958 --> 10:57.308
- No--we apprehended a suspect

10:57.352 --> 11:00.224
for those other attacks,
but ruled him out

11:00.268 --> 11:03.488
for the car bomb
that killed Kathy Stabler.

11:03.532 --> 11:04.489
- Thank you.

11:06.840 --> 11:09.712
- Captain Benson,
good to see you.

11:09.756 --> 11:12.236
As you just testified,
the night of the bombing,

11:12.280 --> 11:14.674
you apprehended another
suspect, not my client,

11:14.717 --> 11:17.198
but a Mr. Jacob Peters.

11:17.241 --> 11:19.330
- Peters was arrested
and charged

11:19.374 --> 11:21.811
with the fire-bombings
of two police vans

11:21.855 --> 11:23.030
three blocks away.

11:23.073 --> 11:24.727
- And didn't Mr. Peters
also take credit

11:24.771 --> 11:25.859
for bombing
the Stabler vehicle?

11:25.902 --> 11:28.470
- He did, but...

11:28.513 --> 11:31.168
we found that the claims
were not credible.

11:31.212 --> 11:33.736
- By "we," you mean you
and Detective Stabler,

11:33.780 --> 11:36.043
the victim's husband.

11:36.086 --> 11:38.567
You allowed him
to interrogate a suspect.

11:38.610 --> 11:42.136
- Detective Stabler was
under my direct supervision,

11:42.179 --> 11:43.572
and I trusted his instinct.

11:43.615 --> 11:44.834
- At any point,
were you concerned about

11:44.878 --> 11:46.183
Detective Stabler losing
his temper?

11:46.227 --> 11:49.317
- No, my take was that
his anger was for show.

11:49.360 --> 11:51.058
- Really?

11:51.101 --> 11:53.538
I'm not sure I saw it that way.

11:53.582 --> 11:54.757
Defense Exhibit A.

11:54.801 --> 11:55.802
- Sorry for your loss,

11:55.845 --> 11:57.107
but there's a war going on,

11:57.151 --> 11:58.674
and your wife bleeding out
on the sidewalk,

11:58.718 --> 12:00.763
she's just another casualty.

12:00.807 --> 12:02.417
- Detective--

12:02.460 --> 12:04.811
- Were you concerned
about what might happen next?

12:04.854 --> 12:07.814
Is that why you got
between him and the suspect?

12:07.857 --> 12:08.858
- The situation was
under control.

12:08.902 --> 12:10.251
- Thanks to you.

12:10.294 --> 12:12.079
In your long partnership
with Detective Stabler,

12:12.122 --> 12:15.560
how many times has
he received command disciplines

12:15.604 --> 12:17.562
and IAB reviews for crossing
the line with a suspect?

12:17.606 --> 12:20.435
- It was all
over ten years ago.

12:20.478 --> 12:23.046
- You were aware
of his history.

12:23.090 --> 12:24.308
In hindsight, wouldn't it
have been better for you

12:24.352 --> 12:26.310
and the NYPD to follow protocol

12:26.354 --> 12:27.616
and recuse him
from this investigation?

12:27.659 --> 12:31.402
- It was
with Detective Stabler's help

12:31.446 --> 12:33.883
that we were able
to arrest Richard Wheatley.

12:33.927 --> 12:35.972
- Does the NYPD condone
vigilantism,

12:36.016 --> 12:38.409
or only if the vigilante
is a member of the NYPD?

12:38.453 --> 12:39.541
Withdrawn.

12:39.584 --> 12:42.544
[tense music]

12:42.587 --> 12:44.764
♪

12:44.807 --> 12:46.548
Nothing further.

12:55.557 --> 12:57.951
- Sergeant Bell,
how long was your task force

12:57.994 --> 12:59.866
monitoring the actions
of Mr. Wheatley's

12:59.909 --> 13:01.215
criminal organization?

13:01.258 --> 13:02.607
- For over a year.

13:02.651 --> 13:05.828
We gathered surveillance
footage, audio recordings.

13:05.872 --> 13:07.525
- So what in your investigation

13:07.569 --> 13:09.266
led you to suspect
that Richard Wheatley

13:09.310 --> 13:11.703
was involved
in Kathy Stabler's murder?

13:11.747 --> 13:13.401
- After we arrested

13:13.444 --> 13:15.664
Mr. Wheatley's head
of security, Izak Bekher,

13:15.707 --> 13:18.275
a subpoena
for his financials turned up

13:18.319 --> 13:22.105
a credit card purchase
of a 4-inch swivel vise.

13:22.149 --> 13:23.063
- Did you ever
find that device?

13:23.106 --> 13:25.065
- Yes, in his storage space.

13:25.108 --> 13:28.285
The Arson and Explosion Squad
linked it

13:28.329 --> 13:30.200
to the bomb
that killed Kathy Stabler.

13:30.244 --> 13:32.507
- Thank you, Sergeant.

13:34.465 --> 13:37.207
- Sergeant Bell, Izak Bekher
was ex-Mossad agent, correct?

13:37.251 --> 13:39.383
- Yes.
- Does it strain credulity

13:39.427 --> 13:41.385
that an ex-Mossad agent
with a multiple encryption

13:41.429 --> 13:45.520
security system would
purchase a bombmaking device

13:45.563 --> 13:48.349
with his own credit card
and then after making the bomb,

13:48.392 --> 13:51.743
keep the incriminating device
in his own storage unit?

13:51.787 --> 13:53.223
- That's what we found.

13:53.267 --> 13:54.659
- Who exactly found
the credit card purchase,

13:54.703 --> 13:58.054
was it a detective
in your unit, Jet Slootmaekers?

13:58.098 --> 13:59.664
- Yes.

13:59.708 --> 14:02.363
She's a highly skilled
cybersecurity expert.

14:02.406 --> 14:04.321
- Did your cybersecurity expert
find any connection

14:04.365 --> 14:08.499
between my client and Izak
Bekher's alleged bombmaking?

14:08.543 --> 14:10.980
- Mr. Wheatley is
a sophisticated criminal

14:11.024 --> 14:13.504
who knows how
to evade detection.

14:13.548 --> 14:16.203
- Just like
his head of security.

14:16.246 --> 14:18.031
Let me ask you this,
which is more likely,

14:18.074 --> 14:21.338
that an ex-Mossad agent
sloppily left

14:21.382 --> 14:24.515
a trail of evidence
for the police to find,

14:24.559 --> 14:26.430
or that the credit card
purchase

14:26.474 --> 14:29.346
and the device were planted
by someone in the NYPD

14:29.390 --> 14:31.174
with a vendetta
against Richard Wheatley?

14:31.218 --> 14:32.523
- That's not what happened.

14:32.567 --> 14:34.134
- Sergeant Bell,
you were with Detective Stabler

14:34.177 --> 14:36.049
when he arrested Izak Bekher.

14:36.092 --> 14:37.920
Considering
that Mr. Bekher's face

14:37.964 --> 14:40.140
was smashed into a fence
and his shoulders dislocated,

14:40.183 --> 14:42.707
would you say that Detective
Stabler used excessive force?

14:42.751 --> 14:45.885
- We had reason to believe
Mr. Bekher was armed,

14:45.928 --> 14:46.929
so I would say no.

14:46.973 --> 14:50.411
- But he was not armed, was he?

14:54.415 --> 14:56.896
Oh, by the way,
isn't your wife's family

14:56.939 --> 14:58.245
currently suing the NYPD

14:58.288 --> 14:59.420
for use of excessive force
against her nephew?

14:59.463 --> 15:02.162
- Objection. Relevance?
- Mr. Barba?

15:02.205 --> 15:03.772
- Uh, I'm not sure
there is any, Your Honor.

15:03.815 --> 15:06.818
I just appreciate the irony.

15:06.862 --> 15:12.520
♪

15:12.563 --> 15:14.739
- [whispering indistinctly]

15:23.183 --> 15:24.619
Captain.

15:26.273 --> 15:27.970
Thank you for meeting with me.

15:28.014 --> 15:29.493
Do you have to be here?

15:29.537 --> 15:30.973
- Technically, you shouldn't
be meeting with someone

15:31.017 --> 15:32.366
who's testified against you.

15:32.409 --> 15:34.063
Yeah, I have to be here.

15:34.107 --> 15:35.760
- And I don't know
why I'm here.

15:35.804 --> 15:38.111
And I'm not gonna be here long,
so cut to the chase.

15:38.154 --> 15:39.503
- I heard about your crash.

15:39.547 --> 15:40.983
And I wanted
to tell you in person,

15:41.027 --> 15:44.508
I can't imagine how frightening
that must have been.

15:44.552 --> 15:46.336
And to give you my word,
I had absolutely nothing to do

15:46.380 --> 15:47.947
with your car
being run off the road.

15:47.990 --> 15:50.558
- Your word?

15:50.601 --> 15:53.430
Like your word
that you had nothing to do

15:53.474 --> 15:54.997
with Kathy Stabler's death?

15:55.041 --> 15:57.521
- The jury's not even out yet.

15:57.565 --> 16:01.003
I do somehow wish we had met
under different circumstances.

16:01.047 --> 16:02.787
- I don't.

16:02.831 --> 16:07.401
But if you have something that
you want to confess to me...

16:10.882 --> 16:12.928
I'll see you in court.

16:12.972 --> 16:15.887
- By the way, before you go,

16:15.931 --> 16:20.457
the love of my life, Angela,
takes the stand tomorrow.

16:20.501 --> 16:22.155
You might want to make sure

16:22.198 --> 16:24.809
Stabler's children
aren't there.

16:24.853 --> 16:27.638
They probably don't want
to hear what she has to say.

16:29.205 --> 16:31.642
And I guess neither do you.

16:44.481 --> 16:47.702
- Hey.
- Hey.

16:47.745 --> 16:49.704
- I heard Barba was tough
on you.

16:49.747 --> 16:52.402
- I'll live.

16:52.446 --> 16:55.579
Angela Wheatley's
testimony is up next.

16:55.623 --> 16:56.928
Any reason
I shouldn't be there?

16:59.322 --> 17:01.759
- Why would you ask me that?

17:01.803 --> 17:03.718
- I was warned.

17:03.761 --> 17:04.719
- By who?

17:07.113 --> 17:11.856
- Whatever happened between
you and Angela, Wheatley knows.

17:11.900 --> 17:14.163
Which means Barba knows,
and they're gonna use it.

17:14.207 --> 17:15.730
- Wheatley doesn't
know anything.

17:15.773 --> 17:17.558
He's just stirring up Barba,
and Barba's stirring you up.

17:17.601 --> 17:19.299
- You're not answering
the question.

17:21.866 --> 17:24.739
- That's none of your business
or the court's.

17:24.782 --> 17:25.957
The question is...

17:27.481 --> 17:29.265
why are you really asking?

17:29.309 --> 17:32.225
[tense music]

17:32.268 --> 17:35.010
- I wish I could trust you,
Elliot.

17:35.054 --> 17:37.447
- Liv, what does that mean?

17:38.796 --> 17:40.015
- [sighs]

17:44.759 --> 17:46.674
I know that
you are carving your way

17:46.717 --> 17:48.719
through a mountain of grief,

17:48.763 --> 17:51.766
and I have tried
to be here for you.

17:53.072 --> 17:56.292
But this is a one-way street,
Elliot.

17:56.336 --> 17:59.600
You have not asked me
one question

17:59.643 --> 18:04.126
about what has happened to me
since you left.

18:04.170 --> 18:06.955
You show up at my house
in the middle of the night

18:06.998 --> 18:11.133
when my son is there asleep.

18:11.177 --> 18:13.788
That was hard for me--

18:13.831 --> 18:15.442
scary.

18:19.968 --> 18:21.317
And this letter.

18:25.408 --> 18:27.758
Why did you give me
that letter?

18:27.802 --> 18:30.935
A letter that you
didn't even write.

18:33.112 --> 18:34.635
What was that about?

18:38.987 --> 18:41.816
- I'm not sure I know.

18:48.910 --> 18:51.391
I guess I didn't know
how to begin.

18:53.393 --> 18:56.135
- Well, that makes two of us.

18:56.178 --> 18:58.746
♪

19:02.228 --> 19:02.402
.

19:02.445 --> 19:05.100
- Last May, I was poisoned
with a nerve agent

19:05.144 --> 19:08.059
that still affects
my cognitive skills

19:08.103 --> 19:10.279
and neurological functioning.

19:10.323 --> 19:12.194
- Have you been able
to return to your job

19:12.238 --> 19:14.327
as a math professor
at Columbia?

19:14.370 --> 19:15.893
- Not yet.

19:15.937 --> 19:17.808
But my memory is clear,

19:17.852 --> 19:21.072
and I am ready
to testify today.

19:21.116 --> 19:22.509
- In your statement
to the police, you said

19:22.552 --> 19:26.165
the defendant told you
that Detective Stabler

19:26.208 --> 19:29.124
"gunned down" your son.
- Yes.

19:29.168 --> 19:33.302
I now know that Richard
was gaslighting me.

19:33.346 --> 19:36.740
My husband--
ex-husband killed my son.

19:36.784 --> 19:38.742
- Objection.
- Sustained.

19:38.786 --> 19:40.266
Jury must disregard.

19:40.309 --> 19:42.398
Mr. Wheatley is not charged
in that crime.

19:42.442 --> 19:44.748
- After the defendant
gaslit you,

19:44.792 --> 19:46.228
what did he say next?

19:46.272 --> 19:49.753
- He asked if I wanted
the detective to die.

19:49.797 --> 19:51.407
I said no.

19:51.451 --> 19:55.890
I wanted him to suffer
like I was suffering.

19:55.933 --> 19:58.197
When I heard
about the car bombing, I--

19:59.546 --> 20:01.678
I felt sick.

20:01.722 --> 20:02.984
- Thank you.

20:05.334 --> 20:06.466
- How you doing,
Miss Wheatley?

20:06.509 --> 20:07.510
I know this is difficult.

20:07.554 --> 20:09.382
You need a--
a break, some water?

20:09.425 --> 20:11.601
- I'm fine, thank you.

20:11.645 --> 20:13.777
- Remember when you
first met Detective Stabler?

20:13.821 --> 20:16.302
At that time, did you believe
that he'd killed your son?

20:16.345 --> 20:18.347
- Yes.

20:18.391 --> 20:19.566
- You must have been
angry at him.

20:19.609 --> 20:21.045
- I was.

20:21.089 --> 20:24.832
- But at some point,
those feelings changed to--

20:24.875 --> 20:26.921
you felt sympathy for him?

20:28.836 --> 20:30.707
- Well, we--
we shared a loss.

20:30.751 --> 20:32.535
- The loss you had engineered?

20:32.579 --> 20:34.276
Forgive me. I'll rephrase.

20:34.320 --> 20:36.974
At what point did you come
to the conclusion

20:37.018 --> 20:41.414
that Detective Stabler
had not killed your son?

20:41.457 --> 20:43.590
- We grew close.

20:43.633 --> 20:45.679
I realized he wasn't capable.

20:45.722 --> 20:46.984
- Close, how close?

20:47.028 --> 20:48.247
- We were--

20:50.031 --> 20:53.164
I've heard it called
"grief partners."

20:53.208 --> 20:55.079
- So there was nothing
between you two, romantically?

20:55.123 --> 20:56.994
- We both had feelings
for each other.

20:57.038 --> 20:58.300
- Those feelings
become physical?

20:58.344 --> 20:59.867
You kissed Detective Stabler,
correct?

20:59.910 --> 21:01.303
- Objection. Relevance?

21:01.347 --> 21:03.436
- Getting there, Your Honor.
- I'll allow.

21:03.479 --> 21:05.438
Witness may answer.

21:05.481 --> 21:06.787
[tense music]

21:06.830 --> 21:08.267
- We kissed once.

21:08.310 --> 21:11.357
But he left before
anything could go further.

21:11.400 --> 21:14.185
- Weren't you hoping
that things would go further?

21:14.229 --> 21:15.665
Hadn't you agreed
to a romantic dinner

21:15.709 --> 21:17.188
with him that same night?

21:17.232 --> 21:19.060
- We wanted to get
to know each other better.

21:19.103 --> 21:20.322
- Yes, but that dinner
never happened

21:20.366 --> 21:23.064
because Bekher told Stabler

21:23.107 --> 21:25.066
that you had ordered
the hit on his wife?

21:25.109 --> 21:26.459
- But I didn't.

21:26.502 --> 21:28.287
- But Stabler believed him,
and arrested you--

21:28.330 --> 21:29.462
- Yes, but--
- Who interrogated you

21:29.505 --> 21:31.202
after your arrest?

21:32.987 --> 21:34.118
- I--

21:37.731 --> 21:41.517
I asked for Elliot 'cause
I wanted to tell him the truth.

21:41.561 --> 21:43.824
- The truth or you wanted
to blame Kathy Stabler's murder

21:43.867 --> 21:45.521
on your ex-husband
so that the man that you were

21:45.565 --> 21:47.610
having romantic feelings for
wouldn't know

21:47.654 --> 21:50.744
that you had helped
arrange his wife's murder?

21:50.787 --> 21:52.528
- That's not how it happened.

21:52.572 --> 21:54.487
That's--I--I can't think.

21:54.530 --> 21:55.879
- You didn't have
feelings for him?

21:55.923 --> 21:57.141
You weren't in love with him?

21:57.185 --> 21:58.882
You are under oath,
Professor Wheatley.

21:58.926 --> 22:06.107
♪

22:10.851 --> 22:13.549
- Yes.

22:13.593 --> 22:15.334
I was in love with him.

22:20.817 --> 22:21.818
- Are you still
in love with him?

22:21.862 --> 22:23.603
- Objection.
- Sustained.

22:24.952 --> 22:27.998
- I wish I wasn't.

22:28.042 --> 22:31.828
I didn't ask for any
of that to happen.

22:31.872 --> 22:34.440
- No.

22:34.483 --> 22:38.357
All you asked for was
for Elliot Stabler to suffer.

22:38.400 --> 22:40.010
Withdrawn.

22:40.054 --> 22:47.148
♪

23:01.162 --> 23:03.730
- The hell kind of soap opera
are you running?

23:03.773 --> 23:07.734
Asking my ex-wife if she's
still in love with him!

23:07.777 --> 23:08.996
- I got the jury to see

23:09.039 --> 23:10.476
that your co-conspirator
has a motive to lie.

23:10.519 --> 23:12.173
- There's got to be a dozen
other ways to do that

23:12.216 --> 23:14.088
without making me look
like his goddamn cuck!

23:14.131 --> 23:17.570
- Maybe, but as your reaction
proves, this one resonated.

23:17.613 --> 23:19.354
I need a win.
Your son's testifying next.

23:19.398 --> 23:20.790
It's gonna be damning.

23:20.834 --> 23:22.270
- Richie?
[chuckles]

23:22.313 --> 23:24.054
I wouldn't worry about him.

23:24.098 --> 23:25.752
The kid's wet the bed
his whole life.

23:30.496 --> 23:31.584
- Richie, you're currently

23:31.627 --> 23:33.324
awaiting trial
on murder charges.

23:33.368 --> 23:35.109
Did the state offer you
any consideration

23:35.152 --> 23:36.763
for your testimony?

23:36.806 --> 23:39.069
- No, they did not.
- Can you tell the jury

23:39.113 --> 23:42.333
why you're testifying
against your own father?

23:42.377 --> 23:45.554
- Because he lied to me,
our family.

23:45.598 --> 23:47.904
Look, he caused the deaths
of my grandfather,

23:47.948 --> 23:49.428
my half-brother, and Gina.

23:49.471 --> 23:50.777
- Objection.
- Sustained.

23:50.820 --> 23:52.474
- You've always blamed
everyone else, Richie.

23:52.518 --> 23:53.823
Isn't it time you grow up?

23:53.867 --> 23:56.173
- Mr. Wheatley,
do not address the witness.

23:56.217 --> 23:57.348
- You don't want to do this,
son.

23:57.392 --> 23:58.698
- Mr. Wheatley, that is enough.

23:58.741 --> 24:00.787
Mr. Barba,
please control your client.

24:00.830 --> 24:04.530
Mr. Carisi,
the objection is sustained.

24:04.573 --> 24:06.967
- Of course, Your Honor.
I'll get right to the point.

24:07.010 --> 24:08.490
Richie--

24:08.534 --> 24:11.493
hey, Richie, you with us?
- Uh, yeah.

24:11.537 --> 24:14.191
- Tell the jury what
you overheard your father say

24:14.235 --> 24:16.280
to Izak Bekher.

24:16.324 --> 24:19.240
- Uh, yeah.
He--

24:27.466 --> 24:31.034
- Richie, do you--
do you need a moment?

24:31.078 --> 24:34.124
- No. No, I'm good.

24:34.168 --> 24:36.126
I, um--

24:37.606 --> 24:39.347
I don't recall what I heard.

24:39.390 --> 24:42.481
[people murmuring]

24:44.657 --> 24:45.875
- What?

24:45.919 --> 24:50.445
♪

24:50.489 --> 24:53.404
Richie, I have here your
statement to the DA's office

24:53.448 --> 24:55.885
saying that you overheard
your father, Richard Wheatley,

24:55.929 --> 24:59.759
order Izak Bekher to arrange
the murder of Kathy Stabler.

24:59.802 --> 25:02.457
- I don't recall that.
- You're under oath, Richie.

25:05.852 --> 25:08.245
- I lied.

25:08.289 --> 25:10.378
I--I was angry with--
with my father

25:10.421 --> 25:12.554
and blamed him, like he said.

25:14.382 --> 25:16.906
I don't recall
hearing anything.

25:16.950 --> 25:18.778
I didn't hear anything.

25:18.821 --> 25:20.083
[people chattering]

25:20.127 --> 25:22.216
- Order! Order!

25:22.259 --> 25:29.397
♪

25:35.185 --> 25:35.403
.

25:35.446 --> 25:37.579
- What the hell just happened?

25:37.623 --> 25:39.059
- The facility swears
that Richie was under guard,

25:39.102 --> 25:40.626
that there was no breach
in security.

25:40.669 --> 25:42.018
- They're lying.
Somebody got to him.

25:42.062 --> 25:43.585
- No, not somebody--
Wheatley.

25:43.629 --> 25:45.674
- Either way,
it put us in a hole.

25:45.718 --> 25:48.024
The good news is,
you're up next, Detective.

25:48.068 --> 25:50.897
Barba's whole defense is that
you are out of control.

25:50.940 --> 25:54.857
I need you calm
and collected up there.

25:54.901 --> 25:56.293
- Okay, no problem.

26:00.515 --> 26:02.822
- Counselor,
there something on your mind?

26:02.865 --> 26:04.171
- Right now, there is no reason

26:04.214 --> 26:05.651
for Richard Wheatley
to take the stand.

26:05.694 --> 26:08.567
- He got in Richie's head
or worse.

26:08.610 --> 26:11.439
- Don't let him get into yours.
You know this guy.

26:11.482 --> 26:13.615
Find a way to get into his.

26:18.185 --> 26:21.014
Detective, this is painful,
but can you tell the jury

26:21.057 --> 26:22.755
what happened the night
your rental car was bombed?

26:22.798 --> 26:25.584
- We were late to an event.

26:25.627 --> 26:28.935
I took a call, which I later
found out was spoofed.

26:28.978 --> 26:31.459
I gave Kathy the keys.
She went to get the car.

26:31.502 --> 26:32.765
There was an explosion.

26:32.808 --> 26:35.071
- But she survived the blast?
- She did.

26:35.115 --> 26:37.596
I rode with her
to Mercy Hospital.

26:37.639 --> 26:40.773
She regained consciousness.
I told her I loved her.

26:40.816 --> 26:43.123
But she died from her injuries

26:43.166 --> 26:45.995
on the operating table
a few days later.

26:46.039 --> 26:48.737
- Who was in charge of the
investigation into her death?

26:48.781 --> 26:50.652
- NYPD Intelligence Unit.

26:50.696 --> 26:51.958
- And how
did you become involved?

26:52.001 --> 26:53.742
- I'd been
investigating Manfredi Sinatra,

26:53.786 --> 26:55.265
Richard Wheatley's father,

26:55.309 --> 26:59.269
through my work with the NYPD
liaison office in Rome.

26:59.313 --> 27:02.577
I subsequently raided one
of his Brooklyn warehouses

27:02.621 --> 27:03.970
that Richard Wheatley operated.

27:04.013 --> 27:05.362
- What did you find there?

27:05.406 --> 27:07.887
- A copy
of my international police ID.

27:07.930 --> 27:10.150
I realized right then
I was being tracked.

27:10.193 --> 27:11.194
- And what led you to suspect

27:11.238 --> 27:12.587
that Richard Wheatley was
involved?

27:12.631 --> 27:14.241
- Richard Wheatley
was the boss.

27:14.284 --> 27:16.504
And in my experience,
the order to green-light

27:16.547 --> 27:19.072
a hit on a police officer,
let alone his wife,

27:19.115 --> 27:20.464
always comes from the top.

27:20.508 --> 27:22.858
- Did you confront Wheatley?
- He confronted me.

27:22.902 --> 27:26.427
He told me
to leave his ex-wife alone,

27:26.470 --> 27:31.214
that neither of our women
should be collateral damage.

27:31.258 --> 27:34.478
To which I said,
"Like my wife?"

27:34.522 --> 27:35.958
- And how did he respond?

27:36.002 --> 27:38.439
- He claimed he was sorry
for my loss.

27:38.482 --> 27:43.400
He did not deny responsibility
for that loss.

27:43.444 --> 27:45.402
- Thank you, Detective.

27:48.928 --> 27:50.712
- Detective,
let me say sincerely

27:50.756 --> 27:52.714
how sorry I am for your loss.

27:55.891 --> 27:58.241
My task here today is to prove

27:58.285 --> 28:01.114
to this jury
that there is no proof

28:01.157 --> 28:03.725
that my client was in any way
responsible for that loss.

28:03.769 --> 28:05.379
- I know Wheatley killed
my wife.

28:05.422 --> 28:06.859
- I know
that you believe that today,

28:06.902 --> 28:07.816
but didn't you
initially believe

28:07.860 --> 28:09.252
that Izak Bekher
was responsible?

28:09.296 --> 28:12.342
- As I said earlier,
the order comes from the top.

28:12.386 --> 28:15.215
Izak Bekher was only acting
on his orders.

28:15.258 --> 28:16.869
- Didn't Bekher tell you
that actually he was acting

28:16.912 --> 28:18.566
on Angela Wheatley's orders?

28:18.609 --> 28:20.350
- He did try to blame her, yes.

28:20.394 --> 28:21.874
- You subsequently
arrested her,

28:21.917 --> 28:23.745
so you must've
believed that too?

28:23.789 --> 28:25.355
- I believed she had
some involvement,

28:25.399 --> 28:27.662
but I quickly realized that
Wheatley had manipulated her.

28:27.706 --> 28:28.881
- Yeah, she's testified
to that,

28:28.924 --> 28:30.404
but what's not clear
is whether she turned

28:30.447 --> 28:32.362
on her ex-husband
to get herself a better deal

28:32.406 --> 28:35.061
or to keep herself
in your good graces--or both.

28:35.104 --> 28:36.715
- Objection.
Is there a question here?

28:36.758 --> 28:39.021
- Sustained.
Move it along, Mr. Barba.

28:39.065 --> 28:40.414
And, Detective Stabler,

28:40.457 --> 28:42.590
only answer the questions
you're asked.

28:42.633 --> 28:44.635
- Detective Stabler, it seems
to me like you're lurching

28:44.679 --> 28:45.941
from one suspect to another

28:45.985 --> 28:47.900
in a frantic attempt
to someone to accuse.

28:47.943 --> 28:50.250
- I am neither lurching
nor frantic.

28:50.293 --> 28:51.730
- How often do you think
about this case?

28:51.773 --> 28:52.905
Every week, every month?

28:52.948 --> 28:54.776
- Every minute of every day.

28:54.820 --> 28:56.604
- You're being treated
for PTSD?

28:56.647 --> 28:58.084
- I was. I am no longer.

28:58.127 --> 28:59.912
- But you are familiar
with the acronym HALT?

28:59.955 --> 29:01.957
Hungry, Angry, Lonely, Tired?

29:02.001 --> 29:03.959
- I am.
- What about your family?

29:04.003 --> 29:05.439
I'm sure this has been
stressful for them.

29:05.482 --> 29:07.963
- Leave my family out of this.
- Just like you did

29:08.007 --> 29:09.269
for the last five months
going undercover?

29:09.312 --> 29:10.661
- Objection.
- Sustained.

29:10.705 --> 29:11.793
Mr. Barba?

29:11.837 --> 29:12.794
- I'm trying
to ask the detective

29:12.838 --> 29:14.796
if his PTSD, his trauma,

29:14.840 --> 29:16.493
family problems,
his work issues,

29:16.537 --> 29:18.147
including watching
a member of his unit

29:18.191 --> 29:19.453
get shot by his sergeant--

29:19.496 --> 29:21.890
- If you're speaking
about Detective Morales,

29:21.934 --> 29:25.676
his dying confession was
that he was paid $200,000

29:25.720 --> 29:27.026
by Richard Wheatley

29:27.069 --> 29:28.549
to kill Angela Wheatley!
- Your Honor.

29:28.592 --> 29:30.420
- Detective Stabler,
you've been warned.

29:30.464 --> 29:32.553
Just answer the questions
you're asked.

29:32.596 --> 29:34.990
Jury will disregard.
- Since you opened the door,

29:35.034 --> 29:37.036
is there anything you don't
blame my client for?

29:37.079 --> 29:38.994
- He is to blame.
He had Izak Bekher killed.

29:39.038 --> 29:40.648
He killed his own father.
He had my wife killed.

29:40.691 --> 29:42.258
- Move to strike, Your Honor!

29:42.302 --> 29:44.086
- Jury will disregard.
Watch yourself--

29:44.130 --> 29:46.306
- He had someone run
my former partner off the road.

29:46.349 --> 29:48.177
- Your Honor, will you stop him
or shall we wait for him

29:48.221 --> 29:50.963
to accuse my client of
kidnapping the Lindbergh baby?

29:51.006 --> 29:52.268
- Detective Stabler,
one more word,

29:52.312 --> 29:53.835
I'm holding you in contempt.

29:53.879 --> 29:56.011
- How much
is Wheatley paying you, Judge?

29:56.055 --> 29:57.839
- That's it.
Detective Stabler,

29:57.883 --> 29:59.188
I'm holding you in contempt.

29:59.232 --> 30:00.973
Officers.

30:01.016 --> 30:03.976
[people chattering]

30:04.019 --> 30:06.935
[tense music]

30:06.979 --> 30:13.507
♪

30:17.119 --> 30:19.513
- Thanks. I owe you.

30:21.645 --> 30:23.560
[toilet flushes]

30:28.043 --> 30:30.176
- Detective.

30:30.219 --> 30:33.135
Well, isn't this awkward?

30:33.179 --> 30:35.877
That was some performance
back there.

30:35.921 --> 30:38.488
Another minute, you'd have
been frothing at the mouth.

30:40.534 --> 30:43.058
- So you were listening, huh?
- Everyone was.

30:43.102 --> 30:45.539
I was surprised to see Olivia
in the gallery.

30:45.582 --> 30:48.107
She didn't hear enough
after Angela's testimony?

30:48.150 --> 30:50.718
You must have had
some mansplaining to do.

30:50.761 --> 30:53.547
- Well, Olivia knows
a lot more about what went on

30:53.590 --> 30:56.071
between me and Angela
than the jury does.

30:57.943 --> 30:59.727
She's good like that.

30:59.770 --> 31:02.077
- Poor Ange.

31:02.121 --> 31:04.253
She's a shell
of her former herself.

31:04.297 --> 31:06.342
Hasn't been the same
since her son died.

31:06.386 --> 31:09.563
- That's not my experience
with Angela.

31:09.606 --> 31:14.089
Seems as if grief
was a powerful aphrodisiac.

31:14.133 --> 31:15.917
- [chuckles]

31:15.961 --> 31:19.486
- She was playing you.
- Yes, she was--

31:19.529 --> 31:21.227
over and over.

31:21.270 --> 31:23.794
- [chuckles]
Look at you,

31:23.838 --> 31:27.581
all puffed out
with your Bayside High bravura.

31:27.624 --> 31:31.019
When this is over,
she'll be right by my side.

31:31.063 --> 31:33.761
- Yeah, maybe so, but trust me,

31:33.804 --> 31:34.762
she'll be thinking of me.

31:34.805 --> 31:36.111
- Let's go, fellas.

31:36.155 --> 31:38.026
Court's back.

31:38.070 --> 31:45.207
♪

31:52.780 --> 31:52.911
.

31:52.954 --> 31:54.390
- Mr. Barba?

31:56.175 --> 32:00.396
- Since the state has failed
to make their case,

32:00.440 --> 32:02.572
the defense at this time rests,
Your Honor.

32:02.616 --> 32:04.357
- Actually,
I'd like to say a few words.

32:04.400 --> 32:05.749
- No, you wouldn't.
Your Honor--

32:05.793 --> 32:07.751
- If Mr. Wheatley is inclined
to take the stand,

32:07.795 --> 32:09.057
we have no objection,
Your Honor.

32:09.101 --> 32:10.406
- I appreciate that, Counselor.

32:10.450 --> 32:11.668
Your Honor,
I need a moment with my client.

32:11.712 --> 32:13.105
- I don't need a moment.
I'd like to testify.

32:13.148 --> 32:14.541
That's my constitutional right.

32:14.584 --> 32:16.499
If my lawyer
won't go along with that,

32:16.543 --> 32:20.112
I'd like to request a change
in representation.

32:20.155 --> 32:22.505
[tense music]

32:22.549 --> 32:28.772
♪

32:28.816 --> 32:31.645
- Mr. Barba?

32:31.688 --> 32:34.213
- Mr. Wheatley is the boss.

32:34.256 --> 32:36.476
His call.

32:44.005 --> 32:46.442
Mr. Wheatley,

32:46.486 --> 32:49.750
can you tell the jury
why we ended up here?

32:49.793 --> 32:53.406
- I ask myself
that question every day.

32:53.449 --> 32:57.323
My sense is Detective Stabler
experienced a terrible tragedy,

32:57.366 --> 33:00.979
and the NYPD, where the blue
line is still quite thick,

33:01.022 --> 33:03.633
allowed him to run
his own rogue investigation

33:03.677 --> 33:06.462
during which he somehow
fixated on implicating me

33:06.506 --> 33:09.465
for a crime I did not commit.

33:09.509 --> 33:11.685
- Why you?
- My guess,

33:11.728 --> 33:13.469
he was in New York to testify

33:13.513 --> 33:15.123
against some gentlemen
from Puglia.

33:15.167 --> 33:20.041
He conflated that investigation
with the death of his wife.

33:20.085 --> 33:23.566
As the jury has seen, once that
man gets something in his head,

33:23.610 --> 33:28.006
he's like a--he's like
a junkyard dog with a bone.

33:28.049 --> 33:30.834
It's probably served him well
as a detective.

33:30.878 --> 33:34.838
He'll grind his teeth
to the nubs,

33:34.882 --> 33:38.668
chewing through that bone,
and then swallow the shards.

33:38.712 --> 33:41.976
- Go on.
- I say that empathically.

33:42.020 --> 33:46.459
I too have suffered
tremendous loss.

33:46.502 --> 33:51.246
My father, my adopted son.

33:51.290 --> 33:54.684
My ex-wife poisoned.

33:54.728 --> 34:01.343
My s--
my son rotting in a jail cell.

34:01.387 --> 34:04.912
My whole family torn apart.

34:04.955 --> 34:07.132
Elliot and I have that
in common.

34:07.175 --> 34:09.003
- Thank you, Mr. Wheatley.

34:11.484 --> 34:15.183
- To be fair
to Detective Stabler,

34:15.227 --> 34:17.142
I am an obvious target.

34:17.185 --> 34:20.493
My father, may he rest in
peace, was a career criminal.

34:20.536 --> 34:24.714
But I'm a business man,
not a murderer.

34:24.758 --> 34:26.760
- Just to be clear,
you had nothing

34:26.803 --> 34:28.588
to do with the murder
of Kathy Stabler?

34:28.631 --> 34:30.720
- Not at all.

34:30.764 --> 34:32.853
Nor did my ex-wife.

34:32.896 --> 34:34.463
- Your ex-wife?
- Angela Wheatley.

34:34.507 --> 34:37.553
It has been suggested that
she conspired with Izak Bekher

34:37.597 --> 34:39.729
to have Kathy Stabler killed.

34:39.773 --> 34:43.777
Nothing could be further
from the truth.

34:43.820 --> 34:45.909
- So what is the truth?

34:45.953 --> 34:48.173
- Despite the prosecution
having pressured her

34:48.216 --> 34:49.913
into testifying against me,

34:49.957 --> 34:52.264
by no stretch of
the imagination does that mean

34:52.307 --> 34:55.397
that either of us set
in motion a contract killing.

34:55.441 --> 34:57.399
That's ridiculous.
- So then who did?

34:57.443 --> 34:59.749
- Izak Bekher,

34:59.793 --> 35:02.100
of his own accord.

35:02.143 --> 35:05.407
When I found out about it,
I confronted him.

35:05.451 --> 35:08.323
I threatened to report him.

35:08.367 --> 35:10.412
As a man
with multiple passports

35:10.456 --> 35:13.241
to multiple countries, he just

35:13.285 --> 35:14.634
slipped into the wind.

35:18.725 --> 35:21.858
- That, uh--
that seems convenient,

35:21.902 --> 35:25.427
implicating the one person
who can't be called to testify?

35:25.471 --> 35:27.386
- Occam's razor.

35:27.429 --> 35:31.216
Simple truths often
seem convenient.

35:31.259 --> 35:33.131
- Aren't you the boss, though?

35:33.174 --> 35:35.785
I mean, how could
an employee unilaterally

35:35.829 --> 35:38.048
murder Kathy Stabler
without your knowledge?

35:38.092 --> 35:39.746
- It was his job
to provide security for me,

35:39.789 --> 35:42.227
not my job to monitor
his every waking moment.

35:42.270 --> 35:44.925
In hindsight, I am guilty

35:44.968 --> 35:47.057
of trusting the wrong man.

35:47.101 --> 35:49.059
- And making sure that guy's
never seen or heard from again,

35:49.103 --> 35:50.539
which seems to be
the fate of Mr. Bekher.

35:50.583 --> 35:52.062
- Objection.
- Withdrawn.

35:52.106 --> 35:55.849
Just to recap,
all the witnesses

35:55.892 --> 35:57.807
to the crimes
that you may have ordered

35:57.851 --> 35:59.853
are now either dead
or incapacitated,

35:59.896 --> 36:02.203
and yet you are not responsible
for any of those attacks?

36:02.247 --> 36:04.031
[laughs]
Oh, Mr. Wheatley,

36:04.074 --> 36:06.990
you--you gotta be the
unluckiest guy in the world.

36:07.034 --> 36:09.906
Or maybe you're the luckiest.
Withdrawn.

36:14.520 --> 36:16.043
Let's start over.

36:18.698 --> 36:21.570
At the time of Rafiq's death,

36:21.614 --> 36:23.833
wasn't he working
as a drug dealer?

36:23.877 --> 36:27.663
- I know it's convenient
to depict all young, Black men

36:27.707 --> 36:30.231
as drug dealers,

36:30.275 --> 36:33.321
but Rafiq was also a poet.

36:33.365 --> 36:34.714
- Yeah, he was a poet,

36:34.757 --> 36:36.759
making his living
selling a bootlegged version

36:36.803 --> 36:39.022
of the street drug
that you manufactured.

36:39.066 --> 36:40.720
A few months later,
you found out

36:40.763 --> 36:42.983
that a rival gang was
doing the same thing.

36:43.026 --> 36:45.246
What happened to them?
- I have no idea

36:45.290 --> 36:46.552
what you're talking about.

36:46.595 --> 36:48.293
- I'll refresh your memory.

36:48.336 --> 36:50.338
They were all gunned down--

36:50.382 --> 36:51.339
just like Rafiq.

36:51.383 --> 36:52.688
- Objection, Your Honor.

36:52.732 --> 36:53.950
How is any of this relevant
to the charges

36:53.994 --> 36:55.822
my client
is standing trial for today?

36:55.865 --> 36:57.258
- It speaks directly to motive,
Your Honor.

36:57.302 --> 37:00.043
It's a question that we've
been circling for days.

37:00.087 --> 37:02.916
Why Kathy Stabler?
- [sighs]

37:02.959 --> 37:04.613
- Wasn't Kathy Stabler murdered

37:04.657 --> 37:06.659
because you couldn't risk
Angela finding out

37:06.702 --> 37:08.487
that it was you
who had executed her son...

37:08.530 --> 37:09.531
- Your honor, objection!

37:09.575 --> 37:11.185
- Because he was
ripping you off?

37:11.229 --> 37:15.145
- Do you really think repeating
that canard over and over

37:15.189 --> 37:17.322
and over will make it
come true?

37:17.365 --> 37:20.716
For the last time,
I didn't have anyone murdered.

37:20.760 --> 37:23.458
If I wanted someone dead,
they would be dead,

37:23.502 --> 37:25.547
including you, Mr. Carisi.

37:25.591 --> 37:28.550
[people chattering]

37:28.594 --> 37:31.684
[tense music]

37:31.727 --> 37:37.864
♪

37:37.907 --> 37:39.909
- I'm sorry, did--

37:39.953 --> 37:41.781
did you just threaten
a prosecuting attorney

37:41.824 --> 37:43.043
in open court?

38:18.861 --> 38:20.167
- Jury's still out.

38:20.210 --> 38:21.560
Judge sent them back
three times.

38:21.603 --> 38:23.692
- It's deadlocked.

38:23.736 --> 38:26.042
So you did your job.

38:26.086 --> 38:28.001
- I would've had an acquittal

38:28.044 --> 38:29.698
if your partner hadn't
feigned losing it,

38:29.742 --> 38:31.613
goaded Wheatley
into testifying.

38:31.657 --> 38:33.659
- You wanted Stabler
to lose it.

38:33.702 --> 38:36.444
- Yeah, and Stabler knew that,

38:36.488 --> 38:38.403
drove into the skid,

38:38.446 --> 38:40.796
even had you bring Angela in.

38:40.840 --> 38:42.450
- So we both did our jobs.

38:42.494 --> 38:44.147
- We did.

38:48.195 --> 38:49.979
Stabler coming back has
made things more complicated--

38:50.023 --> 38:52.330
- So now we're gonna
have small talk?

38:54.027 --> 38:55.811
- You know the problem
with being an empath?

38:57.291 --> 39:00.207
it's too easy to lose yourself
when other people need you.

39:03.515 --> 39:06.779
- Just so we're clear,

39:06.822 --> 39:09.042
I feel betrayed by you.

39:10.783 --> 39:15.265
And I don't know
how I'll ever get over it.

39:17.877 --> 39:19.226
[phone buzzes]

39:22.142 --> 39:23.491
- Liv.

39:23.535 --> 39:25.145
- What?

39:26.886 --> 39:28.104
- Jury's back.

39:37.113 --> 39:40.378
- I'd like you to know,
whichever way this goes,

39:40.421 --> 39:42.336
you did a hell of a job.

39:42.380 --> 39:44.860
I'd like you
to be my consigliere.

39:44.904 --> 39:46.906
- All due respect,

39:46.949 --> 39:48.821
there's not enough money
in the world.

39:50.736 --> 39:52.694
- Where's Eli?
- Studying.

39:52.738 --> 39:53.956
He's doing his homework,

39:54.000 --> 39:55.131
but he's not
answering his phone.

39:55.175 --> 39:57.438
My mom's checking on him.
There she is.

39:57.482 --> 39:58.874
Mama, what's up?

39:58.918 --> 40:00.398
What do you mean
he's not there?

40:00.441 --> 40:01.790
I'm staring right at him.

40:01.834 --> 40:03.444
Hold on a sec.

40:03.488 --> 40:04.532
Look, uh--

40:04.576 --> 40:05.794
Mama, I'm on my way.

40:05.838 --> 40:07.883
Son of a bitch.

40:07.927 --> 40:09.450
He must be looping a video
on the cam.

40:09.494 --> 40:11.104
And he emptied out
her medicine cabinet.

40:11.147 --> 40:13.236
- I'm so sorry, Elliot.

40:14.281 --> 40:16.022
- Has the jury reached
a verdict?

40:16.065 --> 40:17.327
- We have not, Your Honor.

40:17.371 --> 40:19.417
We remain
hopelessly deadlocked.

40:19.460 --> 40:21.680
- Do you think getting
more time might enable you

40:21.723 --> 40:22.898
to come to a verdict?

40:22.942 --> 40:24.334
- No, Your Honor.

40:24.378 --> 40:25.901
- Your Honor,
they've been deliberating

40:25.945 --> 40:27.033
for less than a day.

40:27.076 --> 40:28.469
- Any longer, this could extend

40:28.513 --> 40:30.515
over the holiday break.

40:30.558 --> 40:31.559
We move for a mistrial.

40:31.603 --> 40:34.475
- One day or fourteen,

40:34.519 --> 40:36.782
I'm sorry, I don't see
this being resolved.

40:39.611 --> 40:42.265
I'm declaring a mistrial.

40:42.309 --> 40:45.486
Members of the jury,
I thank you for your service.

40:45.530 --> 40:47.445
Mr. Wheatley, you're remanded.

40:54.147 --> 40:56.105
- What does that mean?
- It means we lost.

40:56.149 --> 40:57.411
- They're gonna
try him again, Elliot.

40:57.455 --> 40:58.630
- Will they?

40:58.673 --> 41:01.589
I have to find my son.

41:01.633 --> 41:04.592
[dramatic music]

41:04.636 --> 41:11.120
♪

41:18.998 --> 41:21.957
[dramatic music]

41:22.001 --> 41:29.138
♪

41:49.028 --> 41:52.161
[wolf howls]
